---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 p-effect="from above">🌐 <span class="main-gradient">WebMCP</span></h2>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <ul class="more-margin">
    <li>
      <span class="main-sub-gradient">W3C proposal</span> by <span
        p-fragment
        p-effect="highlight">Google & Microsoft</span
      > to expose web app features to AI agents
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Adds <code>navigator.modelContext</code> to the browser — a <span
        class="main-sub-gradient">client-side MCP server</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Agents stop <span class="main-sub-gradient">guessing from the UI</span>
      — the app tells them exactly what's possible
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      WebMCP brings MCP into the browser. Instead of screen scraping, a site
      registers its tools via navigator.modelContext and the agent invokes them
      directly — like turning a webpage into an MCP server, entirely
      client-side.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide follow-fragments>
  <h5 class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Registering a tool - imperative mode</span>
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="app.ts">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-typescript">
    await navigator.modelContext.registerTool({
    name: "search-products",
    description: "Search the product catalog by keyword",
    inputSchema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
        query: { type: "string", description: "Search term" }
        },
        required: ["query"]
    },
    </code><p-fragment><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-typescript">
    execute: async ({ query }) => {
        const results = await api.search(query);
        return { content: [
            { type: "text", text: JSON.stringify(results) }
        ] };
    }
    });
</code>
  </p-fragment>
  </pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>Same shape as a regular MCP tool — name, description, inputSchema.</p>
    <p>
      The key difference is <code>execute</code>: it runs in the browser, with
      direct access to app state, the DOM, cookies — everything.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide follow-fragments>
  <h5 class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Registering a tool - declarative mode</span>
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="search-form.html">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-html">
    &lt;form
      toolname="search-products"
      tooldescription="Search the product catalog by keyword"
      action="/search"
    &gt;
      &lt;input
        name="query"
        type="text"
        toolparamdescription="Search term to filter products"
      /&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
</code>
  </pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      In declarative mode, we don't register the tool from JavaScript. We
      describe it directly in HTML.
    </p>
    <p>
      The form becomes the tool: <code>toolname</code> is the tool name,
      <code>tooldescription</code> explains what it does, and form fields become the
      input parameters.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is powerful because existing HTML semantics are reused instead of
      creating a completely separate integration layer.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient" p-effect="from above">Where are we now?</h2>
  <ul class="more-margin">
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Available only in <span class="main-sub-gradient">Chrome, from 149+</span> —
      behind a flag, still experimental ( <code
        >chrome://flags/#enable-webmcp-testing</code
      >)
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Requires an <span class="main-sub-gradient">open browser tab</span> — not a
      headless replacement for backend MCP
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      No cross-browser support yet —
      <span class="main-sub-gradient">standardization in progress</span>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Still experimental — treat it as a preview, not a production standard. The
      key mental model: WebMCP complements backend MCP, it doesn't replace it.
      It shines when the user is actively on the page and the agent assists them
      in context.
    </p>
    <p>
      The exact Chrome version with flag support shifts — always verify current
      status before quoting a specific number in the talk.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<style lang="scss">
  [p-effect~="highlight"] {
    background: linear-gradient(
        color-mix(
          in srgb,
          var(--ending-point-gradient, oklch(0.6 0.1 80deg)),
          transparent var(--highlight-transparency, 85%)
        )
      )
      0 / calc(100% * var(--fragment-progress)) auto no-repeat;
    filter: none;
    &[aria-hidden="false"] {
      border: 1px solid var(--ending-point-gradient);
    }
  }
</style>
